# How will the withdrawal of Russian forces from the west bank of the Dnipro River impact the Ukraine-Russia crisis?

## Summary
Russia has ordered a withdrawal of forces from the west bank of the Dnipro River in the Kherson region <font color=#FF3399>[1]</font>. This is the most significant military development since September when Ukrainian forces swept through the northern Kharkiv region <font color=#FF3399>[2]</font>. President Volodymyr Zelensky has suggested that this withdrawal may just be a strategic move to regroup forces <font color=#FF3399>[3,4]</font>. There is also a one-time payment of 100,000 rubles and a housing certificate for those who choose to leave the Kherson region <font color=#FF3399>[5]</font>. This withdrawal is seen as a show of courage and determination from Ukrainian forces and the importance of continued support from the West and NATO <font color=#FF3399>[1]</font>. The withdrawal of Russian forces from the western bank of the Dnipro River could potentially have a major impact on the Ukraine-Russia crisis, as it is a significant step towards the removal of illegally annexed territory <font color=#FF3399>[1]</font>.

## Claims
| Claim Sentence | Context |
|---|---|
|<font color=#FF3399>[1]</font> Once the withdrawal is complete, several thousand square kilometers of that annexed territory will have been surrendered.<a href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/11/09/europe/ukraine-russia-kherson-withdrawal-intl/index.html" target="_blank">Source</a>| Defending occupied territory on the west bank of Kherson had become increasingly difficult for the Russians as Ukrainian forces disabled bridges across the Dnipro and attacked Russian supply lines. Kherson was one of four Ukrainian regions illegally annexed by Russia in September. Once the withdrawal is complete, several thousand square kilometers of that annexed territory will have been surrendered. The withdrawal "demonstrates the courage, the determination, the commitment of Ukrainian armed forces and also the importance of the continued support" of the West, NATO Secretary General Stoltenberg told CNNs Christiane Amanpour on Wednesday.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[2]</font> The Russian withdrawal would be the most significant military development since Ukrainian forces swept through the northern Kharkiv region in September.<a href="https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/russia-ukraine-war-news-11-09-22/h_1a8a2db31049a52c8097c6cc94f5f4a6" target="_blank">Source</a>| Russian Defense Minister Sergey Shoigu has ordered a withdrawal of Russian forces from the west bank of the Dnipro River in Kherson region, according to Russian state media. His order comes as Ukrainian forces make advances toward the city of Kherson from two directions. The Russian withdrawal would be the most significant military development since Ukrainian forces swept through the northern Kharkiv region in September. Kherson was the first major Ukrainian city and the only regional capital that Russia has captured since the February invasion.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[3]</font> So the fighting isn't over, but the river is a natural barrier that will be difficult for either side to cross.<a href="https://www.npr.org/2022/11/12/1136267844/ukrainians-in-kherson-celebrate-the-withdrawal-of-russian-troops" target="_blank">Source</a>| It says these 30,000 Russian troops that left Kherson and the west bank of the Dnieper River are just a few miles away on the east bank, and setting up defensive positions there. Now, Russia also launched missile strikes at a number of places in southern Ukraine overnight. So the fighting isn't over, but the river is a natural barrier that will be difficult for either side to cross. SIMON: And let's step back for a moment, Greg.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[4]</font> President Volodymyr Zelensky said Wednesday that Russia's announcement of a withdrawal near the southern city of Kherson may be a strategic move to regroup forces.<a href="https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/russia-ukraine-war-news-11-09-22/h_e3118065f3538999d87dba1fa69faa96" target="_blank">Source</a>| President Volodymyr Zelensky said Wednesday that Russia's announcement of a withdrawal near the southern city of Kherson may be a strategic move to regroup forces. But he also said, in an interview with CNN's Christiane Amanpour, that at a time of his choosing, Ukrainian progress on the battlefield would come.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[5]</font> Anyone who leaves the Kherson region will be given "a one-time payment of 100,000 rubles" about $1,600 "and a housing certificate," Stremousov said.<a href="https://www.cnn.com/2022/11/07/europe/kherson-russia-ukraine-intl/index.html" target="_blank">Source</a>| A top Russian-backed official in the city, Kirill Stremousov, said Monday was the last day that Russia offered an "organized evacuation" for civilians from the western bank of the Dnipro River in the occupied portion of the Kherson region. "Most residents who decided to stay in Kherson are only now beginning to realize the gravity of the situation and my warnings," Stremousov, the Russia-appointed deputy head of the Kherson region military administration, said on Telegram. Anyone who leaves the Kherson region will be given "a one-time payment of 100,000 rubles" about $1,600 "and a housing certificate," Stremousov said. Kherson is one of four regions Russia has said it will annex from Ukraine in violation of international law.|
